My relief was momentary as I was immediately forced to reckon with the new reality: dependence on medication to keep me “normal”. Like Susannah Cahalan in her memoir Brain on Fire, I felt tethered to my pills.
She aptly describes how they “embodied contemptible dependence”. As a Miss Independent crown holder, I felt the same way. It was not until I embraced vulnerability as a strength and not a weakness that I truly began my healing.
“How are you?” invites the subject to accept his or her fallibility as a human in a world that celebrates perfection. The woman who cried: "Sirikal saidia!" years back after her house was swept away by floods was answering the question, "How are you?" in the sincerest way possible.
And she was probably better off than the mother who cries herself to sleep, wondering if she should take her own life and her children's to save them from the indignity of poverty. 
Kenyans pride themselves in being resilient people, often taking the curve balls life throws at them in their stride. But sometimes this resilience can stand in the way of wellbeing. 
My wish for you in 2021 is to rediscover the power of vulnerability. Start with asking or answering the question, “How are you?”



